	<h4>Level 1 - Getting Started</h4>
	<h3>Finding the Magician Guild</h3>
	<p>Poof! You appear in Norrath in your starting city. What to do? You want to be a magician…find more magicians! 
	You'll have a note in your inventory that you should read. (Right click it while in windowed interface mode). If you 
	deliver the note, you'll not only know where your guild is located, but you'll be rewarded with experience and a 
	minor item! You can also right click the guild master to train your skills. Many skills go up automatically, without 
	you ever putting a point into them. Scroll down the list to see all of the skills you have. Notice that at the 
	moment, you're not very skilled!&nbsp; In fact, you're downright awful!</p>
	<h3>Training</h3>
	<p>If you wish to train a skill, click the skill box and then click train. Each time you click train, you will spend 
	one training point. You start the game with 5 points and will earn an additional 5 each level. Don't spend all your 
	points just yet. Low-level characters get bonuses for skills to overcome the ineptitude of newbiedom. I recall 
	training piercing…but it isn't necessary. Your skill will improve even if you don't train it. Spell skills will 
	automatically increase as you cast them. More important skills you get later won't work that way. So I suggest 
	saving your training points. You can always come back and train later if you disagree with me. But once you spend 
	the points, they're gone.</p>
	<p>Important starting spell skills include:</p>
	<div align="center">
		<center>
		<table border="1" width="80%">
			<tr>
				<td>Abjuration&nbsp;</td>
				<td>Shielding spells</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>Alteration</td>
				<td>Changing the state of things</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>Conjuration</td>
				<td>Creating something out of thin air, including flying objects to cause damage</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>Divination</td>
				<td>Using magic to know, see or sense something … or turn invisible</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>Evocation</td>
				<td>Damaging things with fire</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>Channeling</td>
				<td>Adeptness at casting spells of all types</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
		</center>
	</div>
	<p>&nbsp;</p>
	<p>Important starting combat skills include:</p>
	<div align="center">
		<center>
		<table border="1" width="80%">
			<tr>
				<td>Piercing</td>
				<td>Your ability to use piercing weapons like a dagger</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>1H Blunt</td>
				<td>Your ability to use a small blunt weapon like a short staff</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>2H Blunt</td>
				<td>Your ability to use a larger blunt weapon like a long staff</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>Throwing</td>
				<td>Your ability to throw small objects like daggers at opponents</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>Bandaging</td>
				<td>Your ability to patch yourself and others up after a fight</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
		</center>
	</div>
	<p>&nbsp;</p>
	<p>Other important starting skills include:</p>
	<div align="center">
		<center>
		<table border="1" width="80%">
			<tr>
				<td>Sense Heading&nbsp;</td>
				<td>Your sense of direction - a skill you will use throughout your career</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td>Swimming</td>
				<td>Your ability to swim - many zones have water - and, in some zones swimming skill is critical</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
		</center>
	</div>
	<p>&nbsp;</p>
	<p>All skills go up as you use them or train them. Of all skills, Sense Heading goes up the slowest. Spam &quot;Sense 
	Heading&quot; repeatedly even if you know exactly where you are. You want to be good at it before you get lost. A neat 
	trick is to add a line to a social to sense heading. For example, when you set up your pet commands at level 4, add 
	a line to each social that senses heading. You'll practice the skill every time you issue a pet command!</p>
	<h3>Spells</h3>
	<p>In EQ, you will need to buy, find, make or quest for your spells.&nbsp; You've already got all the spells you're 
	going to get for free.</p>
	<p>While you're in the magician guild check the various vendors to find which ones sell your spells. Note that you 
	can't afford any spells yet, but hey…there are two of your first spell series in your inventory already! Life is 
	good. To put the spells into your spell book, click on the book icon or type /book. Place a spell onto the cursor by 
	clicking. Drop a spell onto an empty square in the spell book to begin scribing it. This is a good time to get some 
	housework done. Scribing takes a while!</p>
	<p>Once a spell is scribed, you will know it forever. The spell book cannot be dropped, traded, lost or stolen. It 
	will always be right there for you. You cannot erase a spell from the book, but you can move a spell to a new page 
	or square in the book. Just right click the spell you want to move and a new square to which you wish to move it. If 
	the destination square has a spell in it already, the spells will be swapped.</p>
	<p>Before you can cast the spell, you must memorize the spell. As a level 1 you can memorize up to 8 spells. (As a 
	level 60, I can memorize up to 8 spells…the limit remains the same). To memorize a spell, click the scribed spell 
	you wish to memorize and drop it onto one of the 8 empty spell gems. Memorizing takes time as well…but not as much 
	time as scribing. To forget a memorized spell, right click the spell gem. To see what each spell gem contains, hold 
	the ALT key. To cast a spell, click the gem or press ALT-# where the # is 1 - 8.</p>
